TY  - JOUR
AU  - Medoff, James L.
AU  - Abraham, Katharine G.
T1  - Experience, Performance, and Earnings*
PY  - 1980
Y1  - 1980/12/01
DO  - 10.2307/1885488
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 95
IS  - 4
SP  - 703
EP  - 736
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This study provides direct evidence concerning the relationship between experience and performance among managerial and professional employees doing similar work in two major U. S. corporations. The facts presented indicate that while, within grade levels, there is a strong positive association between experience and relative earnings, there is either no association or a negative association between experience and relative rated performance. If we are correct that the performance ratings given to managerial and professional employees in any grade level adequately reflect those employees' relative productivity in the year of assessment, the results imply that the human capital on-the-job training model cannot explain a substantial part of the observed return to labor market experience.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1885488
ER  - 



